===Verb===
{{en-verb|abides|abiding|'''[[abode]]''' ''or'' '''[[abided]]'''|'''[[abode]]''', '''[[abided]]''', ''or (rare)'', '''[[abidden]]'''}}

# {{intransitive|obsolete}} To [[wait]] in expectation; to [[pause]]; to [[delay]]; to [[tarry]].
# {{intransitive}} To [[stay]]; to [[continue]] in a place; to have one's [[abode]]; to [[dwell]]; to [[sojourn]];
#* {{RQ:Authorized Version|Genesis|24|55}}
#*: Let the damsel '''abide''' with us a few days.
# {{intransitive}} To remain [[stable]] or [[fixed]] in some state or condition; to continue; to [[remain]]; to last; to [[endure]].
#* {{RQ:Authorized Version|1 Corinthians|7|20}}
#*: Let every man '''abide''' in the same calling wherein he was called.
# {{intransitive}} To [[remain]]; to be left.
# {{transitive}} To stand ready for; to await for someone.
# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[wait for]], to be prepared for, to [[await]] expectantly, to [[watch]] for.
#* '''1485''', Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book XIII:
#*: Ryght so departed Sir Launcelot and founde hys felyship that '''abode''' hys comming [...].
#* {{RQ:Authorized Version|Acts|20|23}}
#*: Bonds and afflictions '''abide''' me.
#* {{quote-book|title=Idylls of the King|year=1856-1885|passage=I will '''abide''' the coming of my lord.|author=[[w:Alfred Tennyson|Alfred Tennyson]]}}
# {{transitive| obsolete}} To [[endure]] or [[undergo]] a hard trial or a task; to stand up under.
#* {{quote-book|title=Idylls of the King|year=1856-1885|passage={{...}} And shalt '''abide''' her judgment on it.|author=[[w:Alfred Tennyson|Alfred Tennyson]]}}
# {{transitive}} To endure without yielding; to [[withstand]]; await defiantly.
# {{transitive}} To bear [[patiently]]; to [[tolerate]]; to put up with; stand.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 4-2|III-ii}}
#*: She could not '''abide''' Master Shallow.
# {{transitive}} To pay for; to stand the consequences of; to [[answer for]]; to [[suffer]] for; to [[atone]] for.
#* {{quote-book|title=Paradise Lost|passage=How dearly I '''abide''' that boast so vain, {{...}}|author=[[w:John Milton|John Milton]]|year=1667}}
# {{transitive}} To await [[submissive|submisively]]; accept without question; submit to.

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|stand}} Used in the negative form '''can't abide''' is used to indicate strong dislike.

====Quotations====
* "The Dude '''abides'''." Sam Elliot, referring to Jeff Bridges' character, from "The Big Lebowski" a Coen Brothers movie.

